text.text:
I went there because I wanted to buy a good bicycle for my 4 year's old daughter. We had a Gazelle electric bike in the family and visited them just before the corona crisis and we've got served quite good with the new battery so I decide to go to this shop again. Despite a limited choice of two bicycles my daughter fell in love with the red one. I asked the price and I've got "â‚¬449 and no discounts!" Quite strange and unfriendly answer but good things cost money and I said ok, but give me the new one and not the test one with damaged saddle. The answer was "no, that's the only one you'll get, we'll change the saddle". At this point I would already turn and walked away but my daughter was so in love with the red bike that I said "ok, but order me the fenders and check please the bike of my wife, she has the battery problem again". "Your wife's bike is 10 years old and we'll not going to touch it". 6 months ago it was not a problem! Does Gazelle knows they make bicycles for 10 years only? Any way, I paid fully and went away without any will to go there again.
After a week we got a message that our fenders arrived, my wife went there and got one new and one open and scratched. And the reply was "it's for a child bike, it will scratch soon any way"
So got rid of the Gazelle and bought Batavus with a much nicer service. I will never go tho De Geus again.

text.text:
Most expensive cycle parking in Antwerp

Two Danes passing through Antwerp on our bikes, and we wanted to give our bikes an all-around service, since we have been going for over 1000 km.
We had "Bike Project" do the service. We told them that we had some trouble with the spokes breaking on the back wheels of both bikes, so they had to be extra aware of that, but otherwise an all-around service on the rest.
The next day when we came to get our bikes, we were told that there had not been much done, just tightening some loose bolts. So the charge for two hours of work, corresponding to around 150 euros, which would have been fair if they had worked on our bikes, but it seems like they haven't.

The gears on one of the bikes had been bothering us a little, and were still bad when we got the bike.
We only made it 30 km out of Antwerp before one of the spokes broke, and we had to find another bike shop that could fix it. It only took the new bike shop 5 minutes to find the problem; one of the spokes that had been replaced earlier was too big for the wheel, causing the other spokes to break. Also, he adjusted the gears as well.
Furthermore, the front brake on the other bike was very loose and had to be tightened.

I really can't imagine that when you pay for two hours of work for two bikes at a professional bike shop, you don't get a better result.
I can't really feel anything but cheated by that place; come to think of it, it seems more like a very expensive cycle parking than a professional bike shop.

I'm not here to get my money back, but to warn others so they don't feel cheated as well.
